A `taskGroup` applies a single concurrency policy (like `drop`) across multiple distinct tasks. If any task in the group is running, the group's `isRunning` is `true` ŌĆö giving you a single loading indicator for multiple operations. The `drop` policy on the group means only one task across the entire group runs at a time. This is useful for "load panel data" scenarios where clicking any load button while one is in progress should be ignored.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PollLiveScore extends Component {
  // ŌØī Using raw Promise setTimeout ŌĆö NOT cancellation-safe
  pollWithRawTimeout = task(async () => {
    while (true) {
      await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 3000))
      // Even if task is cancelled, setTimeout fires and code continues
      await fetch('/api/live-score') // runs even after component destroyed!
    }
  })

  // Ō£ģ Using ember-concurrency timeout() ŌĆö cancellation-safe
  pollWithTimeout = task(async () => {
    while (true) {
      await timeout(3000) // this is a cancellation point
      // If task cancelled during timeout, execution STOPS HERE
      const res = await fetch('/api/live-score')
      const data = await res.json()
      console.log('Score:', data.runs)
    }
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.pollWithTimeout)}}>Poll</button>
    <button {{on "click" (fn this.pollWithTimeout.cancelAll)}}>Stop</button>
  </template>
}
```

`timeout()` from ember-concurrency is a special awaitable that integrates with the task's cancellation mechanism. When the task is cancelled, any pending `timeout()` is immediately resolved and cancellation propagates ŌĆö the code after `await timeout()` never runs. A raw `setTimeout` wrapped in a Promise schedules a macrotask outside ember-concurrency's control; even if the task is cancelled, the callback fires, leading to potential updates on destroyed components. Always use `timeout()` for delays inside tasks.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, waitForEvent } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class ScoreboardWebSocket extends Component {
  listenForUpdates = task(async () => {
    const ws = new WebSocket('wss://api.spordium.com/live')

    // Ō£ģ waitForEvent ŌĆö cancellation-safe, auto-cleans up listener
    const openEvent = await waitForEvent(ws, 'open')
    console.log('WebSocket connected')

    while (true) {
      const messageEvent = await waitForEvent(ws, 'message')
      const data = JSON.parse(messageEvent.data)
      console.log('Score update:', data.runs)
