`all()` from ember-concurrency behaves like `Promise.all()` but is cancellation-aware. If the containing task is cancelled while `await all([...])` is pending, the remaining promises are abandoned and do not update component state. `Promise.all()` continues running all its promises regardless of task cancellation ŌĆö they complete in the background with no way to stop them. Prefer `all()` whenever running parallel operations inside a task that might be cancelled or restarted.

