`task.performCount` is a counter that increments each time `.perform()` is called, including calls that are dropped or cancelled before running. It's primarily a debugging tool: if `performCount` is significantly higher than `numRunning + numQueued`, many calls are being silently dropped ŌĆö which might indicate an event handler firing too frequently (e.g., scroll events, resize events). It's also useful in tests to assert that a task was triggered the expected number of times.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

// ŌØī Manual @tracked approach ŌĆö error-prone, verbose
class ManualLoader {
  @tracked isLoading = false
  @tracked data = null
  @tracked error = null

  async load(id) {
    this.isLoading = true
    this.error = null
    try {
      const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${id}`)
      this.data = await res.json() // runs even if component destroyed!
    } catch(e) {
      this.error = e // also runs after destroy!
    } finally {
      this.isLoading = false // isLoading might never reset on cancel
    }
    // No concurrency control ŌĆö double-click = 2 parallel fetches
  }
}

// Ō£ģ ember-concurrency ŌĆö all of the above, handled automatically
export default class BetterLoader extends Component {
  loadMatch = task({ drop: true }, async (id) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${id}`)
    return await res.json()
    // isRunning auto-resets, error captured in .last.error,
    // cancelled on destroy, drop prevents double-fetch
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.loadMatch.isRunning}}<p>Loading...</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.loadMatch.last.error}}<p>Error!</p>{{/if}}
    <p>{{this.loadMatch.lastSuccessful.value.venue}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

The `@tracked isLoading` pattern requires: resetting the flag in `finally`, separate `@tracked error` and `@tracked data` variables, manual concurrency prevention, and manual cancellation in `willDestroy`. That's 10+ lines of boilerplate for every async operation. ember-concurrency replaces all of it with one `task()` call plus a concurrency modifier. It also handles the "update after destroy" bug that the manual approach is always vulnerable to.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class DataImporter extends Component {
  // Composition: enqueue (queue extras) + maxConcurrency (allow N parallel)
  importMatch = task({ enqueue: true, maxConcurrency: 3 }, async (matchData) => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/import/match', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify(matchData)
    })
    return await res.json()
  })

  // Composition: drop (ignore extras) + maxConcurrency (allow N parallel)
  // = at most N running, new calls dropped if all N slots busy
  prefetchFixture = task({ drop: true, maxConcurrency: 2 }, async (fixtureId) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/fixtures/${fixtureId}`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  importAll = () => {
    this.args.matches.forEach(m => this.importMatch.perform(m))
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.importAll}}>Import All</button>
    <p>Running: {{this.importMatch.numRunning}} | Queued: {{this.importMatch.numQueued}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

The modifiers `enqueue`, `drop`, `restartable`, and `keepLatest` are concurrency *policies* that work in combination with `maxConcurrency`. `maxConcurrency` sets the concurrency limit (default 1 when a policy is set), and the policy determines what happens to excess calls. `enqueue + maxConcurrency: 3` = worker pool (3 workers, queue the rest). `drop + maxConcurrency: 3` = allow 3 parallel, drop the rest. `restartable + maxConcurrency: 3` = allow 3, cancel oldest when a 4th arrives. You cannot combine `enqueue` with `restartable` or `keepLatest` ŌĆö only one queue policy applies.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class ScoreCard extends Component {
  fetchScore = task(async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`)
    return await res.json()
  })

  // 'isRunning', 'isIdle', 'last', etc. are DERIVED STATE
  // They are NOT stored separately ŌĆö they're computed from the task's internal instances
  // isRunning = numRunning > 0 (derived)
  // isIdle = !isRunning (derived)
  // last = most recent TaskInstance (derived pointer)
  // lastSuccessful = last instance where .isSuccessful === true (derived)

  <template>
    {{! isIdle is simply !isRunning ŌĆö no extra tracking needed }}
    {{#if this.fetchScore.isIdle}}
      <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchScore this.args.matchId)}}>
        Load Score
      </button>
    {{else}}
      <span class="animate-pulse">Fetching...</span>
    {{/if}}

    {{! All these update automatically because they're derived from tracked internals }}
    <p>Perform count: {{this.fetchScore.performCount}}</p>
    <p>Currently running: {{this.fetchScore.numRunning}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

"Derived state" means that properties like `isRunning`, `isIdle`, and `lastSuccessful` are not stored as independent values ŌĆö they're computed on-the-fly from the task's internal set of `TaskInstance` objects. `isRunning` is derived by checking if any instance has `isRunning === true`. `lastSuccessful` is derived by finding the most recent instance with `isSuccessful === true`. This means there's no state synchronization bugs: derived state is always mathematically consistent with the actual task instances, and Glimmer's tracking system ensures templates update correctly.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class TournamentStats extends Component {
  // Ō£ģ No memory leak ŌĆö task is cancelled and dereferenced on component destroy
  loadStats = task(async (tournamentId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/tournaments/${tournamentId}/stats`)
    const data = await res.json()
    // Component might be destroyed before this line runs
    // But because this is a task: execution stops at the await above on cancellation
    // The closure, the response, and 'data' are all GC-eligible after task ends
    return data
  })

  // ŌØī Memory leak with raw async:
  async loadStatsLeak(id) {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/tournaments/${id}/stats`)
    const data = await res.json()
    // Component is destroyed, but this closure still holds a reference to:
    // - 'this' (the destroyed component)
    // - 'res' (the Response object)
    // - 'data' (the full JSON object)
    // None of these can be GC'd until the Promise chain resolves
    this.stats = data // error: updating destroyed component
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.loadStats this.args.tournamentId)}}>Load</button>
  </template>
}
```

Raw async method closures capture `this` (the component), keeping it alive in memory until the Promise resolves ŌĆö even after the component is removed from the DOM. With many pending requests and fast navigation, this accumulates destroyed component instances in memory. ember-concurrency cancels tasks on component destruction, which breaks the closure chain and allows `this`, the response, and all captured variables to be garbage-collected immediately. This is especially important for polling tasks or slow network requests on frequently-navigated routes.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, all } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchDayBundle extends Component {
  loadBundle = task(async (matchId) => {
    try {
      // If fetchScore throws, fetchLineup and fetchWeather are abandoned
      const [score, lineup, weather] = await all([
        fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`).then(r => {
          if (!r.ok) throw new Error('Score fetch failed')
          return r.json()
        }),
        fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/lineup`).then(r => r.json()),
        fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/weather`).then(r => r.json())
      ])
      return { score, lineup, weather }
    } catch (error) {
      // Error from any one of the three propagates here
      console.error('Bundle load failed:', error.message)
      throw error
    }
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.loadBundle.last.error}}
      <p class="text-red-600">Failed: {{this.loadBundle.last.error.message}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.loadBundle this.args.matchId)}}>Load</button>
  </template>
}
```

`all()` from ember-concurrency behaves like `Promise.all()` on rejection: if any one promise rejects, the entire `all()` rejects with that error and the remaining pending promises are abandoned (not cancelled ŌĆö native Promises can't be cancelled, but their results are ignored). The error propagates up to the task function where it can be caught in a `try/catch`. This fail-fast behavior is usually desirable: if one critical piece of match data fails, you don't want to render a partial UI with missing data.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task, race, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class ResilienceDemo extends Component {
  fetchWithFallback = task(async (matchId) => {
    const TIMEOUT_MS = 4000

    const result = await race([
      // Primary: live API
      fetch(`https://live.api/matches/${matchId}`).then(r => r.json()),
      // Fallback: cached CDN version
      fetch(`https://cdn.cache/matches/${matchId}`).then(r => r.json()),
      // Timeout sentinel
      timeout(TIMEOUT_MS).then(() => ({ cached: true, runs: 0, fallback: true }))
    ])

    if (result.fallback) console.warn('Using fallback: timeout reached')
    return result
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchWithFallback this.args.matchId)}}>
      Load
    </button>
    {{#if this.fetchWithFallback.last.value.fallback}}
      <span class="text-yellow-500">ŌÜĀ Cached data</span>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

When `race()` resolves (the first promise wins), ember-concurrency stops tracking the remaining promises ŌĆö their callbacks don't run and they can't update the component. For native Promises this means they complete silently in the background with no effect. For ember-concurrency TaskInstances passed to `race()`, they are actively cancelled. The key benefit is that the "loser" cannot cause side effects or update state after `race()` resolves, unlike `Promise.race()` where losing callbacks still fire.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking'

// ŌØī Antipattern: storing TaskInstance in @tracked
class BadPattern extends Component {
  @tracked currentFetch = null

  fetchScore = task(async (matchId) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  load = (matchId) => {
    this.currentFetch = this.fetchScore.perform(matchId)
    // Storing instance in @tracked causes extra renders
    // AND task.last already gives you this ŌĆö duplication!
  }
}

// Ō£ģ Correct: use task.last ŌĆö already reactive and always current
export default class GoodPattern extends Component {
  fetchScore = task(async (matchId) => {
    return await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`).then(r => r.json())
  })

  load = (matchId) => {
    this.fetchScore.perform(matchId)
    // task.last automatically points to this new instance
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (fn this.load this.args.matchId)}}>Load</button>
    {{! Use task.last instead of a @tracked instance variable }}
    <p>{{this.fetchScore.last.value.runs}}</p>
    {{#if this.fetchScore.last.isRunning}}<span>Loading...</span>{{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

`task.last` is already a reactive pointer to the most recent TaskInstance ŌĆö it updates automatically and triggers template re-renders. Storing the instance in `@tracked` creates redundant state that must stay in sync, causes extra re-renders when the `@tracked` variable is set, and duplicates what `task.last` already provides. The only legitimate reason to hold a TaskInstance reference is for calling `instance.cancel()` to cancel a specific individual execution, and even then you don't need `@tracked` ŌĆö a plain local variable suffices.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchUpdater extends Component {
  updateScore = task(async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}/score`)
    const data = await res.json()

    // Ō£ģ No run() needed ŌĆö ember-concurrency resumes tasks inside the runloop automatically
    // State updates here automatically trigger Glimmer re-renders
    return data

    // ŌØī You would NOT need to do this:
    // import { run } from '@ember/runloop'
    // return run(() => data) ŌĆö unnecessary with ember-concurrency
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.updateScore this.args.matchId)}}>Update</button>
    <p>{{this.updateScore.last.value.runs}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

ember-concurrency automatically wraps task resumptions (the code after each `await`) inside Ember's runloop. This means that when a `fetch()` resolves and your task continues, any `@tracked` mutations or reactive state changes are already batched inside a runloop backfill. You do not need to manually wrap continuations with `run()` or `schedule()`. This is one of the hidden benefits over raw `async/await`, where resumptions after `await fetch(...)` happen outside the runloop and can require manual `run()` calls in older Ember versions.

```gjs
import Service from '@ember/service'
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency'

// Service-level task: lives for the entire app session
export default class LiveScoreService extends Service {
  // This task is NOT cancelled when individual components are destroyed
  pollLiveScores = task(async () => {
    while (true) {
      const res = await fetch('/api/live-scores')
      const data = await res.json()
      this.latestScores = data
      await timeout(10_000)
    }
  })
}

// Component consuming the service ŌĆö component can be destroyed/recreated
// but polling continues in the service
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { service } from '@ember/service'

export default class ScoreWidget extends Component {
  @service liveScore

  <template>
    {{! liveScore.pollLiveScores.isRunning ŌĆö reflects service task state }}
    {{#if this.liveScore.pollLiveScores.isRunning}}
      <span class="text-green-500">ŌŚÅ Live</span>
    {{/if}}
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.liveScore.pollLiveScores)}}>Start</button>
  </template>
}
```

Component-level tasks are cancelled when the component is destroyed. Service-level tasks live as long as the service (typically the entire app session). Put tasks in services when: the operation should persist across route changes (live score polling, WebSocket connection management), the data is shared between multiple components, or the task controls app-wide state. Component tasks are appropriate for data local to that component ŌĆö fetching data for a specific card, handling a form submission. Service tasks handle shared, persistent, or cross-component operations.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class MatchDetailPanel extends Component {
  // drop applies ONLY to fetchScore ŌĆö independent of other tasks
  fetchScore = task({ drop: true }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/score').then(r => r.json())
  })

  // restartable applies ONLY to fetchCommentary ŌĆö independent of fetchScore
  fetchCommentary = task({ restartable: true }, async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/commentary').then(r => r.json())
  })

  // No modifier ŌĆö runs concurrently with everything
  fetchWeather = task(async () => {
    return await fetch('/api/weather').then(r => r.json())
  })

  loadAll = () => {
    // All three can run simultaneously ŌĆö each has its own policy
    this.fetchScore.perform()
    this.fetchCommentary.perform()
    this.fetchWeather.perform()
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.loadAll}}>Load All</button>
    <p>Score: {{#if this.fetchScore.isRunning}}...{{else}}{{this.fetchScore.last.value.runs}}{{/if}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

Concurrency modifiers (`drop`, `restartable`, `keepLatest`, `enqueue`) are scoped to the individual task, not the component class. Two tasks in the same component are completely independent by default ŌĆö one running does not block or affect the other. To apply a shared policy across multiple tasks, you need `taskGroup`. This means you can have fine-grained control: a `drop` on a save button, a `restartable` on a search box, and an `enqueue` on an event logger, all living on the same component without interfering with each other.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

// ŌØī Raw async event handler ŌĆö memory leak on route change
class LeakyHandler extends Component {
  handleClick = async (event) => {
    // When route changes mid-fetch:
    // 1. Component is destroyed
    // 2. But this Promise closure keeps 'this' alive
    // 3. GC cannot collect the component
    // 4. When fetch resolves, 'this' is a zombie ŌĆö alive but not rendered
    const res = await fetch('/api/score')
    const data = await res.json()
    this.score = data // updating zombie component ŌĆö memory leak + potential error
  }
}

// Ō£ģ Task-based handler ŌĆö auto-cancelled on component destroy
export default class SafeHandler extends Component {
  fetchOnClick = task(async () => {
    const res = await fetch('/api/score')
    return await res.json()
    // If component destroyed during fetch: task cancelled, closure released
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" (perform this.fetchOnClick)}}>Load Score</button>
    <p>{{this.fetchOnClick.last.value.runs}}</p>
  </template>
}
```

A raw `async` function creates a Promise that holds a closure over `this`. If the component is destroyed (route change) before the `await` resolves, the GC sees the Promise still holds a reference to `this` ŌĆö the component cannot be collected. After resolution, the code after `await` runs on a destroyed object, which may throw errors or silently corrupt state. ember-concurrency tasks register with `@ember/destroyable`, so on component destruction, tasks are cancelled, the closure chain breaks, and `this` becomes eligible for garbage collection immediately.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerCard extends Component {
  // The problem this solves:
  // 1. Component renders, task starts fetching
  // 2. User navigates away ŌĆö component destroyed
  // 3. Fetch completes 2s later
  // 4. WITHOUT task: code tries to set @tracked on destroyed component ŌåÆ error/leak
  // 5. WITH task: fetch is cancelled at await point on destroy ŌåÆ code never runs

  fetchPlayerStats = task(async (playerId) => {
    await fetch(`/api/players/${playerId}`) // ŌåÉ task cancelled HERE on destroy
    const data = await fetch(`/api/players/${playerId}/stats`).then(r => r.json())
    // Lines below NEVER run if component destroyed before line above resolves
    return data
  })

  <template>
    {{#if this.fetchPlayerStats.isRunning}}
      <div class="animate-pulse">Loading player...</div>
    {{else}}
      <div>{{this.fetchPlayerStats.last.value.battingAverage}}</div>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```

In React, `setState()` on an unmounted component throws a warning and can cause subtle bugs. Ember has the same class of bug with `@tracked` mutations on destroyed components. ember-concurrency solves this by cancelling tasks when their owning component is destroyed ŌĆö code after a cancelled `await` point simply never executes. You get the same protection React's `useEffect` cleanup functions provide, but automatically, without writing any cleanup code. This is one of the strongest arguments for ember-concurrency over manual async patterns in Ember.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'
import { service } from '@ember/service'

export default class TournamentDashboard extends Component {
  @service router

  // Route-like data loading in a component ŌĆö full lifecycle control
  loadTournamentData = task({ drop: true }, async (tournamentId) => {
    const [tournament, fixtures, standings] = await Promise.all([
